english:
  title: Postface to the Record of Filial Conduct
  author: Gwon Geun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    My great-uncle, Lord Changhwa, whose name was Jun, rose to the rank of Kai-fu and lived past sixty years. In serving my great-grandfather, the learned Munjong—whose courtesy name was Pu—he showed such tender devotion morning and evening that he won the old man's affection. He also commissioned an artisan to paint the portraits of the ancient twenty-four filial exemplars and asked Ikjae to write inscriptions for them as a gift. His hope was that these images would bring joy to my ancestor's heart and make him forget the weight of his years. Delighted with the work, my great-grandfather transcribed thirty-eight additional accounts with his own hand and had Ikjae compose inscriptions for these as well. Thus was born the Record of Filial Conduct.

    My great-grandfather rose to become Chancellor, yet in serving my grandfather Muncheong, he fulfilled his duty as a son with complete sincerity. Later, when he presided over all the officials as an elder statesman of the realm, his sons and sons-in-law all achieved high office—the family was said to have had nine enfeoffed lords. Though such splendor and abundance of honor were rare even in antiquity, he remained ever frugal and disciplined. Rich, yet devoted to propriety; exalted, yet devoted to learning. In the intervals of his duties as prime minister, his hands never released a book. He once annotated the Silver Tower Collection in twenty volumes, and in his eighties, after extensive research into the classics, he personally compiled and perfected this Record, laboring with brush and ink even in old age without ceasing. The inscriptions by Ikjae are clear, concise, and incisive—written so that all may easily understand.

    Once, Confucius composed the Classic of Filial Piety, encompassing all conditions: from the nobility of the Son of Heaven above to the lowliness of the common people below; from the care of even a single hair below to the dignity of the grave at last. He left nothing unsaid in instructing all generations in the way children must serve their parents. This Record, likewise, lacks nothing in its treatment of the rightful relationships between high and low, beginning and end. Moreover, it records what the Classic of Filial Piety did not address—the extraordinary circumstances and unforeseen calamities of human relations. Though some examples may seem to exceed the measured mean of the sages, yet the sincerity of children serving their parents must reach this depth before it achieves perfection. Can one fault such devotion for exceeding propriety?

    Confucius compiled the Book of Poetry so that students, through singing and recitation, might cultivate the right feelings of their nature. He composed the Spring and Autumn Annals believing that recorded deeds convey truth far more penetratingly than mere words alone. The accounts in this Record are deeds of the ancients made manifest and clear; the inscriptions too invite recitation and can stir the heart. If this work were widely distributed among the villages and hamlets to instruct the young, and they heard it recited morning and evening until familiarity awakened their goodness and stirred their innate nature, then all people might practice the deeds of Zengzi and Mincius—fulfilling the sage's intention in composing scripture for all ages, and aiding the realm's transformation of its people. Though small, this book bears great fruit for moral instruction. How can one dismiss it merely because it comes from recent times?

    Reading this work deepens my reverence, for within it dwells the refined spirit of my ancestor. In the summer of the third year of Yongle, while on leave, I obtained a newly printed edition from Gaegyeom and found textual errors, which I corrected. Moved thereby, I have ventured—despite my poor learning—to append notes to each section. I claim no new insights; I merely wish to express my sincere devotion to these ancestors. Since the original work arranged accounts by thematic parallels rather than chronological order, in my annotations too I have not endeavored to clarify their dates, lacking as I do home library resources and broad learning. Moreover, I completed this work in less than ten days of writing, thus had no leisure for careful research. I defer further additions to a later time. Yet in doing so, I am further struck by my great-grandfather's vast erudition, and lament my own shallow learning. Will not future readers rightly fault me as a mere child playing at interpretation? Written this sixth month of the year.
  footnotes:
    - Yongle 3 refers to 1405 CE, during the Ming Dynasty.
    - Zengzi and Mincius were two of Confucius's most filially devoted disciples, often cited as exemplars of filial piety.
    - The Record of Filial Conduct (孝行錄) was a compilation of historical examples of filial devotion, intended as moral instruction for the people.
    - Gwon Geun was a prominent Korean scholar-official of the early Joseon Dynasty and a prolific author and editor.
